{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657463/1924011801/0259.xml":{"full_text":"LOCAL TYPfITHETAE\nHONMNKUN\n\u201cPatron Saint\u2019s\u201d Birthday\nObserved With Dinner and\nDance at City Club.\nThe Typothetae of Washington cele\nbrated the birthday of Benjamin\nFranklin, their \"patron saint,\u201d at the\nFity Club last night with a dinner\nand dance, attended by 400 people.\nWilliam John Eynon, president, was\nmaster of ceremonies. It was the\nlargest event ever held by the master\nprinters and representatives of the\nallied industries of this city.\nThe principal speaker was John\nClyde Oswald, editor of the American\nPrinter and a member of the National\nThrift Committee. He spoke on the\n\"Life of Benjamin Franklin.\u201d on\nwhich he has written several books.\nEarlier in the day, at the Thrift week\nexercise at Keith\u2019s Theater, he shared\nthe program with Postmaster General\nHarry S. New.\nThe exercises opened with an invo\ncation by Rev. Charles T. Warner,\nrector of St. Alban\u2019s. A brief address\nwas made by George K. Horn, presi\ndent ot the United Typothetae of\nAmerica.\nA special skit was arranged by for\nmer President Oscar T. Wright and\nS. Percy Oliver, at the conclusion of\nwhich President Eynon presented Ben\nF. Durr, executive secretary of the\norganization, with an order for a\nclosed car, while George Hill, secre\ntary of the Baltimore Typothetae,\npresented him with a miniature ga\nrage, service station and a Tooner\nville trolley car, in the event of the\nautomobile failing to properly func\ntion.\nCarter Made Member.\nAn engrossed copy of a certificate of\nhonorary membership in the Typo\nihetae of Washington was presented\nto Public Printer George Henry Car\nter by President Eynon. Mr. Carter\nspoke briefly.\nSpecial musical numbers were given\nby Mrs. Florence Howard, soloist, and\na Typothetae quartet composed of\nMessrs. Peter M. Becker, jr., J. Ben\nton Webb, J. E. Cogan and Henry\nRule, with Mrs. Frank B. Keyes, ac\ncompanist. Dancing occupied the re\nmainder of the evening, music being\nJANUARY 17th-23d I j\nSTART AN ACCOUNT NOW\ni in a\nI Building and Loan Association\nI\" 3 Highest Interest Rates Paid on Monthly Deposits\nExemptions From Federal and Municipal Tax\nThis kind of investment helps to solve the housing problem, I\nas the money you deposit assists some one to get a home. J\ni B\n-i- .A. a a a a aa jk Invested in Building Associations s\nI I liTAV C<U flilil ilfllll in the District of Columbia, which I I\nI UVer (PdcftUUUtUUU under supervision of U. S. j\n77 Treasury\nFor further information phone J\nany of the following associations: I\nAmerican Building Association\n300 B Street S. E. Lincoln 131\nColumbia Building Association\n716 Eleventh Street N.W. Main 6543\nI Columbia Permanent Building Association I\nSeventh and E Streets S. W. Main 353\nDistrict Building and Loan Association i\nj 819 Fifteenth Street N.W. Main 8416\nEastern Building Association\n336 Pennsylvania Avenue S. E. Lincoln 1447 j\nI Enterprise Serial Building Association\n643 Louisiana Avenue N.W. Main 350 E\nEquitable Co-operative Building Association ft\n915 F Street N.W. Main 1741\nHome Building Association\nI 2006 Pennsylvania Avenue N.W. Main 5808 W\nNational Permanent Building Association I\ny 929 Ninth Street N.W. Main 1381 I\n1 Northeast Building Association I\n20th and Rhode Island Avenue N. E. North 7188 I\nNorthern Liberty Building Association\nI 511 Seventh Street N.W. Main 6171 I\nOriental Building Association I\nSixth and F Streets N. W. Main 2163 I\nPerpetual Building Association\nEleventh, Cor. E Street N. W. Main 1316 I\nI Washington 6% Permanent Building Association\nt 629 F Street N.W. Main 5395 I\nMAJ. KERR NEW HEAD\nOF SERVICE LEGION\nOrganization Formed to Aid Na\ntional Guard to Have Ban\nquet in March.\nAt the annual meeting of the Mili\ntary Service Legion at the National\nGuard Armory last night officers were\nelected as follows; Maj. Stirling\nKerr, president; Capt. Edward W.\nZea, vice president; Capt. Thomas A.\nGreen, secretary and treasurer. It\nwar. decided to hgld the annual ban\nquet of the legion at Franklin Square\nHotel the first week in March.\nMaj. Gen. Anton Stephan and Col.\nL. M. Prett will be the guests of\nhonor of the evening. The orator\nwill be Reynold Blight of Los An\ngeles, Calif., now residing in Wash\nington in connection with duties of\nthe Scottish Rite of Freemasonry at\nthe House of the Temple.\nThe legion is social organisation\nwith the object of fostering the Na\ntional Guard of the District. It was\ndecided to meet quarterly, with the\nannual banquet at the first meeting\nof the year, in March.\nMaj. Kerr, the new president, ob\ntained his first military experience\nin Troop A, cavalry, of the District\nguard, known as the President\u2019s\nTroop, under Capt. Harry Barbour,\nand was major of the Ist Battalion of\nthe rifle regiment organized by the\nDistrict Commissioners for duty in\nthe District during the late war.\nWIFE CHARGES INFIDELITY.\nElizabeth C. Litton has filed suit\nfor an absolute divorce from Cecil M.\nLitton, who, she claims, deserted her\nand their four-month-old baby\nDecember 15. 1922. They were mar\nried October 22. 1921, and the wife\ni charges misconduct with other\nwomen. Attorney Raymond Neu\ndecker appears for Mr*. Litton.\nfurnished by Meyer Davis\u2019 Orchestra,\ni The entertainment committee in\ncharge of the event was composed of\nP. M. Becker, jr. chairman: S. Percy\nOliver, vice chairman: James D.\nBligh, Daniel V. Chlshelm, Charles\nF. Crane, Will Dunn. Charles Ed\nwards, Kuri V. Elker. Lee E. Eynon.\nOscar Pauth, Cornelius Ford. Frank\nP. Ford, E. W. Huguely, George B.\nKennedy, Sidney Oliver, Cgfroll C.\nRoss. R. A. Packwood, Frank W.\nRowsee, William N. Schaefer, Franc\nE. Sheiry. Allen Smythe, Harry R.\nStanford, H. C. C. Stiles. A1 L. Tenny\nson and Lewis M. Thayer.\nTHE EVENING STAB, WASHINGTON, D. C.. FRIDAY, JANUARY 18. 1924.\nSINGER OF PROMISE\nTO MAKE HER DEBUT\nMrs. Dorothy Mansfield Member\nof Notable Cast in \u201cTalcs\nof Hoffmann.\u201d\nDescribed as a singer of \"splendid\npromise.\u201d Mrs. Dorothy Mansfield,\ndaughter-in-law Os Representative\nMansfield of Texas, will make her\noperatic dehut as\na member of the\nt notable cast of\nartiste who will\nsing \u201cTales of\nHoffman\u201d Monday\nnight at the\nPresident The\nater. Edouard Al\nbion, general di\nrector of the\nWashl n g t o n\nOpera Company,\nr announced today.\nMrs. Mansfield\nwtn in the role\n*1 of Giulletta.\n\"The Introduc\nes. MANSriLLD. tlon of Mrs. Mans- i\nfield to Washing\nton opera lovers is in consonance with\nthe aim and policy of the Washington\nOpera Company.\" Mr. Albion said.\n\u2018\u2018Each of the operas produced by our\ncompany has seen the operatic debut\nof one or more young American sing\ners. and some, at least, of those who 1\nmake their first bow in grand opera\nas members of our company are cer- i\ntain to go far in the musical world.\n\"Mrs. Mansfield's voice is a pure'\nlyric soprano. She Is dainty, petite\nand charming, lias exceptional ability\nas an actress, and should continue\nto rise and gain wider recognition.\n\u201cThe cast for Monday\u2019s perfor\nmance of Tales of Hoffmann has\nbeen gathered solely for Us beauty\nof voice and artistic excellence.\nMabel Garrison\u2019s beautiful soprano is\nuniversally recognized and her sing\ning of her role in \u2018Hoffman\u2019 is known\nto many. Josef Schwarz is recog\nnized in Europe os one of the great\nest Interpreters of the roles he will\nsing Monday; Ralph Errolle, Chica\ngo Opera tenor, created a sensation\nin Chicago early in December when\nhe sang \u2018Lakme\u2019 with Oalll-Curci;\nElizabeth Bonner\u2019s beautiful con\ntralto needs no further introduction\nto Washington; Mr. Ananian, the\ngreat buffo of the Metropolitan Opera\nCompany, also is a member of the\ncast, which Includes Albert Sheffer\nman, Louis Annis and others.\u201d\nSEES PRICE INCREASE\nIF BONUS IS VOTED\nRobert Le Fcvre Predicts Half of\nFive-Billion Fund Would Be\nTurned Into Cub. 1\nIf a soldiers\u2019 bonus were paid, within\nthirty days half of the government\ndrafts would be cashed, Robert Le\nLevre declared at a meeting of the\nThirteen Club lost night at the City.\nClub. Figuring that the bonus repre\nsents an outlay of at least $6,800,000,-\n000, he said that this would mean flood\ning the country with half that amount\nin cash. As a result, he think prices\nwould be boosted and the veterans\nwould be paying excessive prices for\nthings long after their bonuses had\nbeen spent.\nSpeaking on the subject. \u201cWhy I Am\nAgainst the Bonus.\u201d he argued that\nthat any assistance to the veterans\nfrom the government In the form of\nbonuses would not afford any perma\nnent relief. While some of the ex\nservice men might use the money to\nstart in business ventures, etc., he be\nlieves that moat of them would not\nreap any material benefit, either using\nthe extra money for current expenses\nor simply wasting it.\nApropos to the 218th anniversary\nof the birth of Benjamin Franklin,\nthe patron genius of the club and\niwhoso thirteen cardinal principles\n\u2022have been adopted by the organiza\ntion. Vernon P. Xxjwery discussed this\nfamous American and drew the con\nclusion that the work of Franklin in\n\u2022his many fields for the welfare of the\ncountry more than offset those things\nIn his varied career which have been\nheld against him. Frank McAloon\nspoke In favor of Mellon\u2019s tax reduc\ntion program. Charles Bemls dwelt\non the business outlook for 1954\nThe club indorsed the agitation for\nbetter street lighting for the District\non motion of George C. Shinn. Maj.\nJoseph F. Randall presided ahd the\nchairman of the evening was Edgar\nMorris.\nMembers of the Thirteen Club were\nguests of their wives, who compose\nthe Clover Club, at a \"leap year\u201d din\nner and dance the previous evening\nat the Purple Iris in Chevy Chase.\nFour famous American rivers\u2014the\nRio Grande, the Arkansas, the Colorado\nand the Platte\u2014have their origin in\nColorado.\nI $1 Women\u2019s 111 Women\u2019s\nI Kid Glove. Where Your TfoUarr Omni Wart Chemise\n29c BEHBENOS 39c\nbrown gloves. Bal- I] r Daintily lace trim\nance of Xmas SI.OO H I liO* l M \\Y/ med envelope\nI gloves; slightly II 9 fcX-v a. a\u00bb* Ilfl OX.. w chemise. Two\nI crushed. I 1 i pretty styles.\n\nSport IU I\nUp to $9.75 I h K I I Womens Any\nGirls\u2019 Coats JI CC/% I Coats j Boy\u2019s O\u2019Coat\n*A nc I $10.90 v^rto^o\n*LLILL l\\ Sflk Qocked Wool I 1 Zrf= SI OC\nA ind Heather Mix- I |i I 1 \u00bbpJL^,af{)\nFur trimmed, braid I 1 ttire Snort Hose in I II Bolivia. Suedlne j I g M\ntrimmed and sport I UrC SP I II and Novelty Mixture 1\nstyle coats that sold I I prettiest of color- Coats, some nicely c -.|\u00bboloe of the House\nto SIO.OO. Heavy I Ribbed and I ii fur trimmed ano \u2014Chinchillas and Clothe,\nwinter weights. 4to I I K ii some braided, in lin\u00dfto 8, and Mackinaws\n14 years. plain. irregulars. ii; 0l side-tied\nOresae. I Bungalow J,\ntO 85 I 7 I Dresses AH Sizes Ii I\nI *P>a ,Ut; g I -M _/%\u25a0 W _ I Conservative and\nB 6 g I I handsome novelty I\nI Our finest Polret I 1 Waist Union Suits 1 M w 11 c i p.i.-i 1\ni Twills and handsome I and Regular Union I uiIBUC I alClll 3\nj crepe silks and sat- I Suits, in white and j prettily hrald trimmed 1 I Satin\nIns. In new novelty 1 ra heavy j crtTer OTer \u00bbu dresses for j I _ K I\nI styles for women 8 I weight; all sizes. bouse wear; made with I Tan KJd, in every j\nj aiui misses. XL- J Lpockete and *lt. J style heel. J\ni\njh Jy i\\ $5.00 and $4.00| Fascinating c\n$2.69 I Women\u2019s New Spring\nReducing I $339 Silk Blouses IT ATO\nCorsets I I Women\u2019s I I If AI J\n$1 85 I I B Robe s2= I\n*1 I I .$1 .98\nIM.I I|\u00abX .t \u00abm crepe Id|l QO\nCornets of stent contif \"LawT.nct\u201d robing. H knit blouses in beau- B.n _\nPerfect Sgnro,